<li><a href="http://van.physics.uiuc.edu/qa/listing.php?id=1256" class="external text" title="http://van.physics.uiuc.edu/qa/listing.php?id=1256" rel="nofollow">Zero-point energy?</a> "Ask the Van" popular science FAQ at <a href="/wiki/University_of_Illinois_at_Urbana-Champaign" title="University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign">University of Illinois</a>.</li>
<li>Philip Yam, "<a href="http://www.padrak.com/ine/ZPESCIAM.html" class="external text" title="http://www.padrak.com/ine/ZPESCIAM.html" rel="nofollow">Exploiting Zero-point Energy</a>", <i>Scientific American Magazine</i>, December 1997, pp. 82-85.</li>
<li>Matt Visser, <a href="http://homepages.mcs.vuw.ac.nz/~visser/general.shtml#what-zpe" class="external text" title="http://homepages.mcs.vuw.ac.nz/~visser/general.shtml#what-zpe" rel="nofollow">What is the 'zero-point energy' (or 'vacuum energy') in quantum physics? Is it really possible that we could harness this energy?</a> from <i>Scientific American Magazine</i>, <a href="http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?id=follow-up-what-is-the-zer" class="external text" title="http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?id=follow-up-what-is-the-zer" rel="nofollow">August 18, 1997</a></li>
</ul>


